<HEADLINE>
MAC INFORMS HK AUTHORITIES OF TOUR GROUP TRAFFIC MISHAP
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 1 (CNA) 05/01/07  01:46:19 (By Sofia Wu)
</P>
<P>
The Mainland Affairs Council (MAC) has informed the Hong Kong
Government's Constitutional Affairs Bureau of a traffic mishap in
scenic Alishan in southern Taiwan involving a Hong Kong tour
group the day before, an official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Jy-jon, director of the MAC's Department of Hong Kong and
Macau Affairs, said the MAC has asked relevant Hong Kong
authorities to inform the families of the Hong Kong tourists of
the accident in which three Hong Kong citizens were slightly
injured.
</P>
<P>
Quoting reports from Chiayi County police authorities, Tsai said
the three Hong Kong tourists sustained mild cerebral concussion,
arm fractures and pulmonary contusion. Two of them were released
from the hospital after receiving medical treatment and only one
remains in the hospital for further observation, Tsai said,
adding that the hospitalized tourist is in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
If family members of the injured want to come to Taiwan, Tsai
said, the MAC will help with their entry permit applications so
that they can come to Taiwan Tuesday at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
The 13-member Hong Kong tour group was touring Alishan when the
bus they were riding accidentally hit an electric pole in the
scenic mountainous area in the southern county of Chiayi, leaving
three Hong Kong tourists and the group's Taiwanese tour guide
injured, local police said, adding that visibility at the time
was very poor due to heavy fog.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, the Taiwanese tour guide, identified as
Hua Tung-pin, was more seriously injured than any of the other
three Hong Kong tourists. Nevertheless, police said, he is not in
critical condition. He also remains in the hospital for further
observation.
</P>
<P>
The two slightly injured tourists will join the 10 other Hong
Kong tourists in continuing their journey, local travel agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The police are still investigating the cause of the accident.
</P>
